This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with object recognition in images. The use of fMRI measurements of human brain activity also suggests that it could belong to the neural networks and machine learning (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the training process of a machine learning algorithm, which could place it in the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The use of human brain activity as a guide for machine learning also suggests that it could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the potential implications for a new class of hybrid machine learning algorithms, which could place it in the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category.
